{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f5e1a2e3-8619-4434-ab23-e48976d2ee08","content":"The standard approach is to **abstract the file system behind an interface**:\n\n1. **Define an interface** like `IFileSystem` with methods matching what you use (`WriteAllText`, `ReadAllText`, `DirectoryExists`, etc.).\n2. **Create a real implementation** that delegates to `System.IO.File` / `Directory`.\n3. **Inject the interface** into classes that need file I/O.\n4. **Mock it in tests** using your preferred mocking framework.\n\nAlternatively, use the existing **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it provides `IFileSystem` out of the box with a `MockFileSystem` for testing, saving you from hand-rolling wrappers.\n\n```csharp\n// With System.IO.Abstractions:\npublic class MyService\n{\n    private readonly IFileSystem _fs;\n    public MyService(IFileSystem fs) => _fs = fs;\n\n    public string Load(string path) => _fs.File.ReadAllText(path);\n}\n\n// In tests:\nvar fs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>\n{\n    { \"/data/config.json\", new MockFileData(\"{ }\") }\n});\nvar svc = new MyService(fs);\nAssert.Equal(\"{ }\", svc.Load(\"/data/config.json\"));\n```\n\nThis keeps your production code clean and your tests fast with no disk I/O.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cfdea017-8451-4511-a695-b35fc9a6fe92","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. This is a design/architecture question about testability, not a code change request. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":396,"requestId":"1C85:115126:1270C6F:14AED7B:69FD2977"},"id":"f331bf4f-efe7-4d76-9f31-53990dcb30af","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:08:32.577Z","parentId":"efa4d6b9-cce4-42a8-b7d5-e9b2af411cfc"}
